Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

9:11 Defendant Salena J. Miller in court with attorney Liesl E. Nelson.  Sean Edward Froelich appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Froelich files an amended information. Guilty to charge in amended information. 2 years Probation. eligible for expungement. Nelson and Def agree.   Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights form is filed with the court; court reviews with Def. Def pleas guilty to charge in amended information; Nelson stipulates to a factual basis.  COURT ACCEPTS PLEA, FINDS DEF FREELY, INTELLIGENTLY, KNOWINGLY & UNDERSTANDINGLY MADE AND WAIVES CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHTS. Court finds and adjudicates Def guilty of charge in amended information. Froelich addresses sentencing: no restitution requested. Nelson addresses sentencing. Court: S/W 2 years probation: court costs, Agent to look at where the Def is in in her recovery and whether grief counseling is needed, expungment available upon successful completion of probation.   Appeal rights are given to the defendant.
